2026-03-31T20:41:18.264Z JOY-0094 comment.added "Design: Terminal-bound sessions with AI token enforcement\n\nSolution combines hard enforcement (CLI) with soft enforcement (AI instructions):\n\n1. Terminal-bound sessions (sudo model): joy auth creates a session and sets an environment variable in the current shell with a cryptographically signed session ID. resolve_identity() requires this variable and validates its content against the session file (signature, expiry, member match). Without the variable or with an invalid value, no session is found -- even if a session file exists on disk. This isolates authentication per terminal.\n\n2. Guard enforcement: When AI members exist in project.yaml and no authenticated session is found, the guard rejects all write actions (not just manage actions as today). Read-only commands (joy ls, joy show) remain accessible without auth.\n\n3. AI instruction enforcement (soft): AI tool instructions state: If JOY_TOKEN is not set, do not execute Joy write commands. Request a delegation token from the user. No mention of the session mechanism -- only the token requirement. This prevents AI tools from piggybacking on the human session in the same terminal.\n\n4. joy ai setup triggers joy auth init: When the first AI member is registered, auth becomes mandatory for the project. This is the activation threshold -- projects without AI members remain frictionless.\n\nThreat coverage:\n- AI in different terminal: hard block (no session variable)\n- AI in same terminal: soft block (instructions refuse without token)\n- Forged session variable: hard block (cryptographic validation fails)\n- AI ignores instructions: out of scope (malicious tool threat model)" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-31T20:51:41.113Z JOY-0094 comment.added "Design update: TTY-bound sessions instead of env var\n\nReplaced the JOY_SESSION environment variable approach with TTY binding. joy auth records the current terminal device (e.g. /dev/pts/1) in the session. resolve_identity() only accepts human sessions where the stored TTY matches the current terminal. This is completely invisible to the user -- no export, no visible mechanism.\n\nTerminal isolation:\n- Human in Terminal A, authenticated: TTY matches, session valid\n- AI in Terminal B: different TTY, session ignored, must use JOY_TOKEN\n- AI in same terminal: same TTY, session valid, soft block via AI instructions\n- CI/cron (no TTY): no match, must use JOY_TOKEN\n\nDeliberate TTY spoofing is out of scope -- that requires active manipulation, not accidental impersonation.\n\nAI instruction rule: If JOY_TOKEN is not set, do not execute Joy write commands. Request a delegation token.\n\nSession validation already happens on every command via Context::load() -> resolve_identity() -> check_session(). The TTY check integrates into the existing validation -- no new architecture needed." [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-31T21:19:39.329Z JOY-0094 comment.added "[x] Added tty field to SessionClaims for terminal-bound sessions\n[x] Implemented current_tty() with Unix (libc::ttyname) and Windows Terminal (WT_SESSION) support\n[x] TTY captured automatically on human session creation, skipped for AI sessions\n[x] check_session() validates TTY match for human sessions\n[x] Guard rejects all write actions for unauthenticated members when AI members exist\n[x] AI instructions updated: no JOY_TOKEN = no write commands, with user-facing message template\n[x] Two new guard tests for auth enforcement with/without AI members\n[x] All 235 tests passing" [horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
